[1]
Date: Wed 7 Sep 2005
From: Les Sims <apvis@bigpond.net.au>

H5N1 avian influenza - migratory birds
--------------------------------------
I have long been skeptical of claims relating to the spread of H5N1 viruses
by wild birds in Asia, especially in countries with endemic infection, with
large populations of free-ranging domestic waterfowl, and where the sale of
susceptible poultry occurs through poorly regulated live bird markets (see
Sims, et al. Vet Rec 2005; 157: 159-64, referred to previously in
ProMED-mail posting 20050824.2492).
However, there are some outbreaks in Asia where spread via trade in
domestic poultry/poultry products, or through movement of contaminated
items used in the poultry industry, appears to be extremely unlikely. The
recent outbreak in wild birds in Mongolia is by far the least convincing.
Mongolia has a tiny commercial poultry industry concentrated largely around
Ulaanbaatar and has very few "village-level" poultry, which removes the
"background noise" associated with the presence of domestic poultry that
complicates analysis elsewhere.
In the Mongolian case, there are few plausible explanations for the
outbreak other than through introduction by a wild bird. However, if this
were the case, it raises questions as to how this occurred, especially
given that the timing of the outbreak does not match the movement of
migratory birds (as has been argued by others, see, for example,
20050906.2637), and, so far, clinically healthy wild birds have tested
negative for H5N1 viruses.
To explain this outbreak, the possibility of silent amplification in some
species for a period of time following introduction needs to be considered.
Not all H5N1 viruses are uniformly fatal in ducks, even though they are
still highly pathogenic for other poultry (and perhaps other wild birds).
Alternatively, low level mortalities in some sites could go unnoticed for
some time, and in less densely populated lakes, spread would not
necessarily be explosive.
The density of birds at some breeding sites provides an ideal environment
for spread and amplification of an H5N1 avian influenza virus. All it would
take for a virus to establish in such a population is the entry of one
infected bird excreting virus. We know that experimentally-infected
mallards can excrete Asian H5N1 viruses for up to 17 days, and, therefore,
introduction of an H5N1 virus by an asymptomatic short-term "carrier" duck
is a possibility.
Why have tests on healthy wild birds been negative? Perhaps short term
"carrier" birds are rare, and given our limited capacity to collect and
test samples, negative results do not rule out this possibility. Also, if
these samples are collected from places where virus was introduced some
time previously, the original "carrier(s)" may no longer be excreting virus.
The Mongolian case provides the best evidence to date for wild birds in the
trans-boundary spread of H5N1 avian influenza, and there is no reason to
believe that this was an isolated occurrence.
--
Les Sims
Asia Pacific Veterinary Information Services
PO Box 353
Manunda
Queensland 4870
Australia
<apvis@bigpond.net.au>
