Date: Wed 7 Sep 2005
From: Howard Pharo <Howard.Pharo@maf.govt.nz>

Avian influenza and migratory birds
-----------------------------------
I refer to part 2 of the posting "Avian influenza - Asia (21): migratory
birds" [20050906.2637], in which George Arzey of the NSW DPI suggested that
the absence or relative absence of AI in Australasia was somewhat
enigmatic, in view of the large numbers of migratory water birds visiting
Australia and New Zealand.
The most obvious explanation for the infrequent occurrence of HPAI in
Australia and its absence from New Zealand is that birds of the order
_Anseriformes_ (ducks & geese) do not migrate across the equator, a point
that is made somewhat in passing in the above-mentioned posting. This
important fact means that Australasian ducks and geese do not mix with the
northern hemisphere populations of these species that are currently the
focus of so much speculation concerning their role in the spread of avian
influenza viruses.
In the case of New Zealand, apart from seabirds in the order
_Procellariiformes_ (albatrosses, petrels, shearwaters etc), the majority
of migratory birds are shorebirds in the order _Charadriiformes_,
particularly sandpipers and their allies in the family _Scolopacidae_. Of
the 14 species of ducks and geese in New Zealand, 8 are endemic/native, and
6 were introduced (mainly from Great Britain) in the 19th century. However,
none of these _Anseriforms_ are migratory, not even within the southern
hemisphere.
Although there has never been an outbreak of HPAI in New Zealand, the
Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry has long been aware of the theoretical
risk of introduction of avian influenza viruses by migratory birds, and
Biosecurity New Zealand has been monitoring this over a number of years,
primarily through surveys of migratory birds soon after their arrival in
this country. The number of samples collected each season has varied, but
in 2004 and 2005, for example, about 300 cloacal swabs were collected from
godwits and knots and a further 580 samples were collected from wrybills, a
non-migratory species of wader that is in very close contact with the
migrants from the time of their arrival in New Zealand. In addition, 900
swabs were taken from fresh feces of knots & wrybills off the ground. No
avian influenza viruses were isolated from any of these samples or from the
less intensive sampling that was conducted in previous years.
A number of surveys of New Zealand's resident duck population have been
carried out over many years. A number of avian influenza viruses have been
isolated, including one H5 in 1997 and one H7 in 2005, but no HPAI viruses
have ever been found.
While it is recognized that it is theoretically possible for any H5 or H7
virus to mutate to pathogenicity if introduced into poultry flocks,
limiting the interface between wild birds (whether migratory or not) and
poultry flocks through good biosecurity practices is key to minimizing the
likelihood of this happening. In practice, this primarily means that water
and feed supplies for poultry flocks must be managed so that they do not
become contaminated with feces of wild birds.
--
Howard J Pharo
Team Manager, Risk Analysis (Animal Kingdom)
Biosecurity New Zealand
Ministry of Agriculture & Forestry
ASB Bank House
101-103 The Terrace
PO Box 2526
Wellington
New Zealand
<Howard.Pharo@maf.govt.nz>
