Date: Wed 7 Sep 2005
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters alert news, 6 Sep 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L06521821.htm>

EU sees tufted ducks, gulls as high bird flu risk
-------------------------------------------------
EU animal health experts have issued guidelines for testing wild birds to
guard against bird flu and identified 15 species that may pose a higher
risk of transmitting the virus, the European Commission said on Tuesday [6
Sep 2005].
The guidelines focus on surveillance and sampling along the birds' major
migration paths and in areas where there is a risk of wild birds mixing
with domestic poultry, such as in ponds. Both living and dead birds are
included, especially where there are cases of abnormal death or significant
disease outbreaks, it said in a statement issued after a meeting of
national EU veterinary, virology and ornithology experts.
The wild birds deemed to present a higher risk of bird flu included common
species such as the teal and mallard, as well as the tufted duck, northern
lapwing, and some goose and gull types.
So far, EU experts and the Commission say that bird flu has only a remote
or low chance of striking the European Union in the immediate future and
that there is no need for governments to ban farmers from keeping poultry
outdoors, as the Dutch have done.
EU animal health experts will meet again in Brussels on 14 Sep 2005 to
evaluate national bird flu surveillance programs drafted by each of the
EU's 25 member states. In August 2005, Russian authorities confirmed a
virulent strain of the disease, potentially lethal to humans, in 6 regions
in Siberia and the Urals, causing the deaths of some 14 000 wild and
domestic fowl. The virus also spread into Kazakhstan.
Some experts fear migratory birds could spread the virus to the EU as they
move to warmer areas for winter after nesting in Siberia, although the
Commission has said this seems unlikely.
